n age groups rather than generating solutions. This collection introduces and explores the growing field of generational studies, providing a comprehensive overview of its strengths and limitations. With contributions from academics across a range of disciplines, the book showcases the concept's interdisciplinary potential by applying a generational lens to fields including sociology, literature, history, psychology, media studies and politics. Offering fresh perspectives, this original collection is a valuable addition to the field, opening new avenues for generational thinking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aAmigoni, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBristow, Jennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBristow, Jennie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuklijas, Tatjana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingstone, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingstone, Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLittle, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuspini, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSomers, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinch, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4htt